<TITLE> Tory MP defects to Brown's Labour </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, June 26 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Conservative MP Quentin Davies defected to Labour on Tuesday, saying the Tories had "no bedrock," in a propaganda coup for Gordon Brown as he prepares to become Prime Minister on Wednesday. "Under your leadership the Conservative Party appears to me to have ceased collectively to believe in anything, or to stand for anything," Davies told party leader David Cameron in a letter posted on the Conservative.home.com Web site. "It exists on shifting sands," he added. "A sense of mission has been replaced by a PR agenda." Davies has been an MP for 20 years, and served as Parliamentary Private Secretary at the Department for Education and the Home Office when the Conservative Party was in power. Since 1997 he has represented Grantham, birthplace of former Tory Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher. He told Sky News that time and again he found Tory policy confused and not properly thought out on a range of issues including Europe, Iraq and the NHS. "I do not think David Cameron is one of those people who has a clear framework in his mind of what the country needs, what he wants to achieve, what the bottom line is, what the right approach to politics is and what the wrong approach to politics is," he said. The defection is good news for Brown, who takes over as Prime Minister from Tony Blair on Wednesday. On the backbenches, Davies served on the Treasury Select Committee, the European Scrutiny Committee and the Standards and Privileges Committee. He has also been opposition spokesman for Social Security and Pensions, Defence and Northern Ireland. He was named Guardian Parliamentarian of the Year and Radio 4 Backbencher of the Year in 1996 and given the Spectator Backbencher of the Year award in 1998. His entry on the Conservative Party Web site describes him as an "independent-minded and outspoken MP", with a long-standing record of expertise in financial and economic affai
